The Observer</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-8107206456.4630452b62a352</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Media (as a channel to the public)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2011/jun/19/women-language-boardroom-study</gtr:url><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The principal research insights and findings were as follows:



1. Whether male or female, leaders recognised as 'effective' by their colleagues use a broadly similar range of linguistic strategies. However, men feel they are expected to use strategies stereotypically coded feminine, whereas women feel they are expected to use strategies stereotypically coded masculine if they are to make an impact. Whereas men using linguistic strategies coded feminine are deemed to be 'emotionally intelligent', women using strategies coded masculine are deemed to be 'scary' or 'aggressive'. This can create a prejudice against 'strong' women at boardroom level (Baxter 2010).



2. In their concern not to appear 'aggressive', many senior women may use 'double-voiced discourse' (DvD): the ability to 'second guess' colleagues' agendas and respond pre-emptively. While DvD indicates a sophisticated judgement about using leadership language and may indeed offer a role model to leaders of all genders, it can also be viewed as a weakness because it can make women sound self-deprecating, uncertain of their views, and overly apologetic (Baxter 2011).



3. Many women leaders utilise aspects of 'archetypal' roles (Kanter 1977): the mother, the iron maiden, the Queen Bee, but these should be reconceptualised critically as flexible, discursive strategies rather than as essentialist attributes (Baxter 2012).



4. Business leaders share an understanding of what constitutes 'effective' leadership talk at senior management level. While recognised as a cultural construct, 'effective leadership talk' can be summarised as four aspects of linguistic expertise:



? Leadership goals linguistic repertoire: effective leaders demonstrate the ability to range across these three broad dimensions of leadership language use: transactional, relational and transformational.

? Levels of authority repertoire: effective leaders can deploy a repertoire of linguistic strategies from direct/assertive to indirect/collegiate to demonstrate authority or solidarity with colleagues as appropriate.

? Language used 'above, on and below the agenda': effective leaders use language on different levels of abstraction and concreteness from 'big picture', strategic talk to operational, agenda-driven talk to detailed, examination of small but essential issues.

? 'Double-voiced' discourse (as above): effective leaders know how to modify and adjust their language in light of their colleagues' agendas, concerns and responses.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>There is strong potential for leadership training and development programmes for women leaders from this research. I have given a number of workshops based on the research for CEOs and women's networks.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>9B38D8C3-EF1A-47DE-A7B8-8EF2E30D3B8A</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-1519764514.1927197b2f16fc8</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education,Environment,Healthcare,Government, Democracy and Justice,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://leadershiptalk.blogs.aston.ac.uk/</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E3D5E580-385B-43CE-B1DA-D350D5F0D637</gtr:id><gtr:title>Global archetypes or local practices? : an ESRC research study of the language of women business leaders in the UK</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8b7010d888823c11ebddf5397cfa144a"><gtr:id>8b7010d888823c11ebddf5397cfa144a</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Judith Baxter (Author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>r_7518841985cb3fdf64</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>D47671DF-6748-4041-AD85-BAC80F1404DC</gtr:id><gtr:title>Women of the corporation: A sociolinguistic perspective of senior women's leadership language in the U.K.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Sociolinguistics</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/271727dcb64b268174f3e4d87b2319d7"><gtr:id>271727d